## 5. Circuit Diagrams

Circuit diagrams render inline: `Qx.draw_circuit/2` returns a `Qx.Draw.Image` that Livebook displays via `Kino.Render`.

**Reading a circuit diagram:** Time flows left to right. Horizontal lines are qubit wires. Gate boxes appear on the wire of the qubit they act on. Vertical lines with dots connect multi-qubit gates.

### Bell State Circuit

```elixir
# Expected: 2 qubit wires; H box on q0; vertical line connecting q0 (dot) to q1 (⊕ box) for CX
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.draw_circuit("Bell State: H + CX")
```

### GHZ State Circuit

```elixir
# Expected: 3 qubit wires; H box on q0; CX from q0 to q1; CX from q1 to q2
Qx.create_circuit(3)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.cx(1, 2)
|> Qx.draw_circuit("GHZ State: H + CX + CX")
```

### Toffoli (CCX) Circuit

```elixir
# Expected: 3 qubit wires; X boxes on q0 and q1; CCX with two control dots connected by vertical line to ⊕ target on q2
Qx.create_circuit(3)
|> Qx.x(0)
|> Qx.x(1)
|> Qx.ccx(0, 1, 2)
|> Qx.draw_circuit("Toffoli (CCX): |110⟩ → |111⟩")
```

### QFT-style Circuit

```elixir
# Expected: 2 qubit wires; H on q0; CP(π/2) spanning q0 and q1 (dot on q0, P(π/2) box on q1); H on q1
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.cp(0, 1, pi / 2)
|> Qx.h(1)
|> Qx.draw_circuit("QFT (2-qubit): H + CP(π/2) + H")
```

### Dagger Gates: S† and T† labels

The v0.11 draw fix: `sdg` and `tdg` render as labelled boxes (previously `sdg` raised `{:unsupported_gate, :sdg}` when drawn).

```elixir
# Expected: 1 qubit wire with four boxes in order: S, S†, T, T† (dagger superscripts visible)
Qx.create_circuit(1)
|> Qx.s(0)
|> Qx.sdg(0)
|> Qx.t(0)
|> Qx.tdg(0)
|> Qx.draw_circuit("Dagger gates: S S† T T†")
```

### Barrier (range form)

`Qx.barrier/2` accepts a list **or a range** (v0.11). Barriers draw as a dashed vertical marker grouping the spanned qubits.

```elixir
# Expected: 3 qubit wires; H boxes on all three; a dashed vertical barrier spanning q0–q2; then CX q0→q1
Qx.create_circuit(3)
|> Qx.h_all()
|> Qx.barrier(0..2)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.draw_circuit("Barrier over 0..2 between H layer and CX")
```

---

## 6. Measurement & Conditional Gates

Shot-based simulation (via `Qx.run/2` with `shots:`) and classical conditional gates (`c_if`) are demonstrated. Results are shown as measurement count histograms.

### Single-Qubit Measurement: |+⟩

A Hadamard gate puts a qubit into equal superposition. Measuring it 1024 times should yield approximately 50% |0⟩ and 50% |1⟩. Exact counts will vary each run — this verifies the probabilistic nature of quantum measurement.

```elixir
# Expected: approximately 500 counts each for "0" and "1" (stochastic — exact split varies per run)
Qx.create_circuit(1, 1)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.measure(0, 0)
|> Qx.run(shots: 1024)
|> Qx.draw_counts(title: "Single-qubit |+⟩ measurement (1024 shots)")
```

### Bell State Measurement (measure_all)

A Bell state Φ+ = (|00⟩ + |11⟩)/√2 is maximally entangled. When measured, qubits are always correlated: only |00⟩ and |11⟩ outcomes appear, each with approximately 50% frequency. `Qx.measure_all/1` measures every qubit into its same-index classical bit in one call.

```elixir
# Expected: approximately 500 counts each for "00" and "11"; "01" and "10" should be absent
Qx.create_circuit(2, 2)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.measure_all()
|> Qx.run(shots: 1024)
|> Qx.draw_counts(title: "Bell state Φ⁺ measurement (1024 shots)")
```

### Conditional Gate (c_if)

`c_if` applies a gate only when a classical bit has a specific value. Here qubit 0 is measured into classical bit 0, then X is applied to qubit 1 only if classical bit 0 equals 1. This means qubit 1 is always set to match qubit 0: both qubits end up equal, so only "00" and "11" can appear — "01" is impossible.

```elixir
# Expected: only "00" and "11" appear (approximately 50/50); "01" must never appear
Qx.create_circuit(2, 2)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.measure(0, 0)
|> Qx.c_if(0, 1, fn qc -> Qx.x(qc, 1) end)
|> Qx.measure(1, 1)
|> Qx.run(shots: 1024)
|> Qx.draw_counts(title: "c_if: qubit 1 mirrors qubit 0 (1024 shots)")
```

---

## 7. Step-Through Inspection

Circuits are recipes — `Qx.steps/2` replays one operation at a time, yielding a `Qx.Step` per instruction. Each step prints as a readable state line, making it the primary state-inspection tool.

### Watch a Bell state build up

```elixir
# Expected: two printed lines —
#   #Qx.Step<0: h(0)  0.707|00⟩ + 0.707|10⟩  cbits: [0, 0]>
#   #Qx.Step<1: cx(0, 1)  0.707|00⟩ + 0.707|11⟩  cbits: [0, 0]>
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.steps()
|> Enum.each(&IO.inspect/1)
```

### Full display map of a step

`Qx.Step.show/1` exposes everything about one step: the Dirac string, amplitudes, and probabilities.

```elixir
# Expected: a map with dirac: "0.707|00⟩ + 0.707|11⟩", amplitudes and probabilities
# lists (|00⟩ and |11⟩ at 0.5 each), index: 1, instruction describing cx(0, 1)
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.steps()
|> Enum.at(-1)
|> Qx.Step.show()
```

### Seeded trajectory (deterministic mid-circuit measurement)

With `seed:`, a mid-circuit measurement collapses the same way on every run — the whole trajectory is reproducible, so the expected output is exact, not statistical.

```elixir
# Expected: exactly three lines (deterministic under seed: 1) —
#   #Qx.Step<0: h(0)  0.707|00⟩ + 0.707|10⟩  cbits: [0, 0]>
#   #Qx.Step<1: measure q0 → c0 ⇒ 1.000|10⟩  cbits: [1, 0]>
#   #Qx.Step<2: c_if(c0==1) x(1) taken  1.000|11⟩  cbits: [1, 0]>
Qx.create_circuit(2, 2)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.measure(0, 0)
|> Qx.c_if(0, 1, fn c -> Qx.x(c, 1) end)
|> Qx.steps(seed: 1)
|> Enum.each(&IO.inspect/1)
```

### Tap functions: peek mid-pipeline

`tap_state/2` and `tap_probabilities/2` run a simulation of the circuit-so-far and hand the result to your function, then return the circuit unchanged — immediate feedback while building a pipeline. (They hide a simulation inside a build step; the docs call this out as a deliberate teaching exception.)

```elixir
# Expected: one printed line — after H: [0.5, 0.0, 0.5, 0.0] — then the final
# histogram shows the Bell distribution (|00⟩ and |11⟩ at 0.5)
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.tap_probabilities(fn p -> IO.inspect(Nx.to_flat_list(p), label: "after H") end)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.draw_histogram(title: "tap_probabilities: peeked mid-build, result unchanged")
```

---

## 8. Composite Patterns & Appenders

The `Qx.Patterns` surface (fronted by `Qx.*`): appenders add a named preparation **at caller-chosen qubits inside a larger circuit** (v0.11), and the broadcast helpers operate on sub-registers.

### bell_pair/4 — Bell pair at offset qubits

`Qx.bell_pair(circuit, q1, q2)` appends the Bell-pair gates onto qubits 1 and 2 of a 3-qubit circuit; qubit 0 is untouched.

```elixir
# Expected: |000⟩ and |011⟩ each have P=0.5 — the pair lives on q1,q2; q0 stays |0⟩
Qx.create_circuit(3)
|> Qx.bell_pair(1, 2)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.draw_histogram(title: "bell_pair(1, 2): entangles q1,q2 only")
```

### ghz/2 — GHZ over a sub-range

`Qx.ghz(circuit, 1..3)` prepares a GHZ state across qubits 1–3 of a 4-qubit circuit.

```elixir
# Expected: |0000⟩ and |0111⟩ each have P=0.5 — GHZ on q1..q3; q0 stays |0⟩
Qx.create_circuit(4)
|> Qx.ghz(1..3)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.draw_histogram(title: "ghz(1..3): GHZ on the upper three qubits")
```

### cx_chain/2 — linear CNOT cascade

```elixir
# Expected: 4 qubit wires; H on q0 then three CX boxes cascading q0→q1→q2→q3
Qx.create_circuit(4)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.cx_chain([0, 1, 2, 3])
|> Qx.draw_circuit("cx_chain: H + CX cascade (4-qubit GHZ)")
```

### h_all/2 — broadcast over a sub-range

```elixir
# Expected: |000⟩, |001⟩, |010⟩, |011⟩ each at P=0.25 — H on q1,q2 only; q0 stays |0⟩
Qx.create_circuit(3)
|> Qx.h_all(1..2)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.draw_histogram(title: "h_all(1..2): uniform over q1,q2 with q0 = |0⟩")
```

---

## 9. OpenQASM Round-Trip

Export a circuit to OpenQASM 3.0 text, inspect it, and re-import it — `to_qasm`/`from_qasm!` live on the `Qx` facade (v0.11). Code generation from a QASM `gate` definition uses the tier-2 `Qx.Export.OpenQASM.from_qasm_function/1` directly (it has no facade delegate).

### Export: to_qasm/2

```elixir
# Expected: printed QASM 3.0 program —
#   OPENQASM 3.0; / include "stdgates.inc"; / qubit[2] q; / bit[0] c;
#   then the gate lines: h q[0]; tdg q[0]; cx q[0], q[1]; barrier q[0], q[1];
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.tdg(0)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.barrier(0..1)
|> Qx.to_qasm()
|> IO.puts()
```

### Round-trip: from_qasm!/1 back to a drawn circuit

The re-imported circuit is instruction-identical — including the native `tdg` (v0.11: no longer decomposed to `phase(-π/4)` on import).

```elixir
# Expected: circuit diagram with H box, T† box, CX q0→q1, and the dashed barrier —
# identical layout to what the exported circuit would draw
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.tdg(0)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.barrier(0..1)
|> Qx.to_qasm()
|> Qx.from_qasm!()
|> Qx.draw_circuit("Round-tripped through OpenQASM")
```

### Code generation: from_qasm_function/1

A QASM `gate` definition becomes a reusable Elixir function (self-contained module source; compile it with `Code.compile_string/1` and call the module it returns).

```elixir
# Expected: printed Elixir module source —
#   defmodule Qx.Generated.Bell_<hash> do / def bell(circuit, a, b) do
#   circuit |> Qx.h(a) |> Qx.cx(a, b) / end / end
qasm_gate = """
OPENQASM 3.0;
include "stdgates.inc";
gate bell a, b {
  h a;
  cx a, b;
}
"""

{:ok, %{name: "bell", arity: 3, source: source}} =
  Qx.Export.OpenQASM.from_qasm_function(qasm_gate)

IO.puts(source)
```

---

## 10. Measurement Bases

`measure_x/3`, `measure_y/3`, and `measure_z/3` measure in the X, Y, and Z bases. Inputs are chosen as eigenstates so the basis choice changes the outcome from deterministic to random.

### X basis on |+⟩ — deterministic

|+⟩ is the +1 eigenstate of X, so an X-basis measurement always yields 0.

```elixir
# Expected: ALL 1024 counts on "0" — no "1" outcomes at all
Qx.create_circuit(1, 1)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.measure_x(0, 0)
|> Qx.run(shots: 1024)
|> Qx.draw_counts(title: "measure_x on |+⟩: always 0")
```

### Y basis on |i⟩ — deterministic

|i⟩ = S|+⟩ is the +1 eigenstate of Y, so a Y-basis measurement always yields 0.

```elixir
# Expected: ALL 1024 counts on "0" — no "1" outcomes at all
Qx.create_circuit(1, 1)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.s(0)
|> Qx.measure_y(0, 0)
|> Qx.run(shots: 1024)
|> Qx.draw_counts(title: "measure_y on |i⟩: always 0")
```

### Z basis on |+⟩ — random

The same |+⟩ state measured in the computational (Z) basis is a coin flip.

```elixir
# Expected: approximately 500 counts each for "0" and "1" (contrast with the X-basis cell above)
Qx.create_circuit(1, 1)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.measure_z(0, 0)
|> Qx.run(shots: 1024)
|> Qx.draw_counts(title: "measure_z on |+⟩: 50/50")
```

---

## 11. Capstone: Quantum Teleportation

Everything composing end-to-end: an arbitrary state prepared with `u/5` on q0 is teleported to q2 via a Bell pair (`bell_pair/4`), a Bell measurement (two mid-circuit measurements), and two classically-conditioned corrections (`c_if`). If the whole stack is healthy, q2 ends up in exactly the state q0 started in.

The input state uses θ = 2π/3, so P(|1⟩) = sin²(π/3) = **0.75** — an asymmetric signature that is easy to spot.

### The teleportation circuit

```elixir
# Expected: 3 qubit wires; U box on q0; H+CX (Bell pair) on q1,q2; CX q0→q1; H q0;
# two measurement symbols (q0→c0, q1→c1); X and Z boxes on q2 (the conditioned corrections)
theta = 2 * pi / 3

teleport =
  Qx.create_circuit(3, 3)
  |> Qx.u(0, theta, 0, 0)
  |> Qx.bell_pair(1, 2)
  |> Qx.cx(0, 1)
  |> Qx.h(0)
  |> Qx.measure(0, 0)
  |> Qx.measure(1, 1)
  |> Qx.c_if(1, 1, fn c -> Qx.x(c, 2) end)
  |> Qx.c_if(0, 1, fn c -> Qx.z(c, 2) end)

Qx.draw_circuit(teleport, "Quantum teleportation: q0 → q2")
```

### Statistical check: q2 carries the 25/75 signature

Measuring all three qubits over many shots: the Bell-measurement prefix (first two bits) is uniformly random across 00/01/10/11, but within **every** prefix the last bit (q2) splits ~25% "0" / ~75% "1" — the teleported state's signature, independent of which corrections fired.

```elixir
# Expected: 8 bars; within each prefix pair the …1 bar is ≈3× the …0 bar
# (e.g. "001" ≈ 3 × "000"); overall the last bit is ≈75% "1"
teleport
|> Qx.measure(2, 2)
|> Qx.run(shots: 4096)
|> Qx.draw_counts(title: "Teleportation: q2 shows 25/75 in every prefix")
```

### State-level check: seeded run + Bloch comparison

With `seed: 2` both corrections fire (Bell outcome 11). After the corrections, q0 and q1 are collapsed, so the final statevector has exactly one nonzero amplitude pair — q2's state. Extract it and compare Bloch spheres: the dot must sit where the input's dot sits.

```elixir
# Expected: Bloch dot in the XZ plane, BELOW the equator toward +X
# (θ = 2π/3 from the north pole) — the input state
Qx.create_circuit(1)
|> Qx.u(0, theta, 0, 0)
|> Qx.get_state()
|> Qx.draw_bloch(title: "Input state on q0")
```

```elixir
# Expected: IDENTICAL dot position to the input-state sphere above
final = teleport |> Qx.steps(seed: 2) |> Enum.at(-1)

# q0,q1 are collapsed: the only nonzero amplitude pair is q2's state
{[a0, a1], _prefix} =
  final.state
  |> Nx.to_flat_list()
  |> Enum.chunk_every(2)
  |> Enum.with_index()
  |> Enum.find(fn {[x, y], _} -> Complex.abs(x) > 1.0e-6 or Complex.abs(y) > 1.0e-6 end)

Qx.draw_bloch(Nx.tensor([a0, a1], type: :c64), title: "Teleported state on q2 (seed: 2)")
```

If the two spheres match, state preparation, entanglement, mid-circuit measurement, classical feedback, the stepper, and the Bloch renderer are all working together correctly.
